daptation in Cities: Toward a Focus on Equity -- t16 Shanghai’s Strive to Excel in Climate Change Adaptation and Low-Carbon Promises: A Model to Follow? -- t17 Adapting New York City: How the Largest US City Is Addressing the Impacts of Climate Change on Its Coastal Communities -- t18 Climate Change Adaptation in Abu Dhabi -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbout the Editors -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPerspectives from worldwide experts on how major cities across the globe are responding to the major environmental threats of our time, including global climate change Over half of the world’s population now lives in cities, and this share is expected to increase in the coming decades. With growing urbanization, cities and their residents face substantial environmental challenges such as higher temperatures, droughts, wildfires, and increased flooding. In response to these pressing challenges, some cities have begun to develop local environmental regulations that supplement national and environmental laws. In so doing, cities have stepped into a role that has been historically dominated by higher levels of government.Global Sustainable Cities takes stock of the policies that have been implemented by cities around the world in recent years in several key areas: water, air pollution, greenhouse gas emissions, and climate adaptation. It examines the advantages—and potential drawbacks—of allowing cities to assume a significant role in environmental regulation, given the legal and political constraints in which cities operate.The contributors present a series of case studies of the actions that seven leading cities—Abu Dhabi, Beijing, Berlin, Delhi, London, New York, and Shanghai—are taking to improve their environments and adapt to climate change. The first volume of its kind, Global Sustainable Cities is a critical comparative assessment of the actions that major cities in the global North and South are taking to advance sustainability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAirxPollutionxGovernment policy2DLC. 0aAirxPollutionxGovernment policy. 0aEnvironmental law2DLC. 0aEnvironmental law. 0aMunicipal corporations2DLC. 0aMunicipal corporations. 0aUrban ecology (Biology) 0aUrban ecology (Biology)2DLC. 7aSCIENCE / Global Warming & Climate Change.2bisacsh  aAbu Dhabi.  aAdaptation.  aAir pollution.  aAir quality.  aBeijing.  aBerlin.  aCOVID-19.  aCarbon neutral.  aClimate adaptation.  aClimate change.  aClimate mitigation.  aClimate policies.  aCoal.  aCoastal city.  aCompressed natural gas.  aCongestion Charging.  aCritical legal studies.  aDelhi.  aDistributed renewable generation.  aDrinking water.  aEcological civilization.  aEconomic growth.  aElectricity.  aEnergy.  aEnvironmental actors.  aEnvironmental protection.  aEnvironmental solutions.  aEquity.  aGHG emissions.  aGlobal cities.  aGovernance structures.  aGreenhouse gas emissions.  aHealth effects.  aHeat waves.  aInclusion.  aIntegral ecology.  aLocal Law 97.  aLocal government.  aLondon.  aLow Emission Zone.  aMass transit.  aNew York City.  aPapal encyclical.  aPope Francis.  aShanghai.  aSocial equity.  aStreets.  aSustainable cities.  aTransportation.  aUrban environmental policy.  aUrbanization.  aVehicle Emissions.  aWastewater.  aWater management.  aWater shortages.  aWater supply.  agreenhouse gases.1 aAnton, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Hanne J. van den, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiswas, Tirtha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChu, Eric K., 